Fedorenko, 2013, published in Tsitologiya i Genetika, 2013, Vol. 47, No. 4, pp. 3–8. Studies into the key mechanisms of regulating the synthesis of antibiotics are one of the central problems of actinomycete genetics and biotechnology. Bioinfor(cid:2) matic analysis data on the genomes of actinomycetes prove the existence of a great number of genes respon(cid:2) sible  for  the  regulation  of  secondary  metabolism  in these  bacteria  [1–3].  However,  detailed  functions  of the majority of regulatory genes have not been studied so far. This problem is especially important for the spe(cid:2) cies of actinomycetes—producers of clinically impor(cid:2) tant antibiotics—the genomes of which have not been sequenced so far. The absence of this information does not give a possibility for thoroughly studying the regu(cid:2) latory elements and the corresponding protein prod(cid:2) ucts which complicates their application for designing superproducer strains. The expression of well(cid:2)studied regulators of secondary metabolism in actinomycetes under heterologous conditions may be used for over(cid:2) coming  these  difficulties.  The  efficiency  of  such  an approach  was  demonstrated  for  some  actinomycete strains [1, 4, 5].

Abstract—Strains of the actinomycetes Streptomyces nogalater Lv65, S. echinatus DSM40730, and S. peuce(cid:2) tius subsp. caesius ATCC27952 are producers of the anthracycline antibiotics nogalamycin, aranciamycin, and doxorubicin, respectively. This work was focused on the impact produced by the expression of the regu(cid:2) latory lndYR and wblAgh genes on the secondary metabolism and morphogenesis of these bacteria. Introduc(cid:2) ing  regulators  into  the  composition  of  replicative  plasmids  in  the  streptomycetes  in  question  leads  to  a decrease in the synthesis of anthracyclines, whereas the expression of lndYR in cells of S. peucetius subsp. cae(cid:2) sius ATCC27952 suppresses the sporulation of the doxorubicin producer which may indicate the presence of their homologues in the genomes. The identification of these genes for the purpose of their further directed inactivation may be a successful tool for obtaining strains with an increased level of synthesis of clinically important compounds, as well as it can allow us to establish particular stages in the regulation of the secondary metabolism of anthracycline antibiotics. Keywords: anthracycline antibiotics, biosynthesis, secondary metabolism, regulatory genes DOI: 10.3103/S0095452713040063 Heterologous Expression of the lndYR and wblAgh Genes in Streptomyces nogalater LV65, S. echinatus DSM40730,  and S. peucetius Subsp. Caesius ATCC27952  (Producers of Anthracycline Antibiotics) D. O. Klymyshina, b, c, O. Ya. Nimetsa, O. M. Stefanyshynb, and V. O. Fedorenkoa a Franko National University, Lviv b Institute of Animal Biology, National Academy of Agrarian Sciences of Ukraine, Lviv, Ukraine c Halytskyi National Medical University, Lviv, Ukraine e(cid:2)mail: dedima@rambler.ru Received June 26, 2012

The gene clusters involved in the biosynthesis of the anthracycline antibiotics nogalamycin, aranciamycin, and  doxorubicin  (Fig.  1)  have  been  cloned  from  the genomes of Streptomyces nogalater, S. echinatus, and S.  peucetius  and  sequenced  [8,  9,  10–12].  Particular aspects in the regulation of secondary metabolism in these bacteria have also been studied [3, 12 and 13], in particular,  the  role  of  some  cloned  pathway(cid:2)specific regulators:  snorA  in  the  control  of  the  nogalamycin biosynthesis and dnrI in the control of the doxorubicin biosynthesis.  A  knockout  of  these  genes  suppresses (whereas  their  overexpression  increases)  the  produc(cid:2) tion level of the corresponding antibiotics which con(cid:2) firms  their  positive  participation  in  regulation  [13]. However, the role of pleiotropic regulatory genes and the possibility of their use for obtaining strains with an increased synthesis level of these compounds have not been studied sufficiently. Of special interest is the het(cid:2) erologous  expression  of  genes  representing  different families of protein regulators. The results obtained in this study give us the possibility to not only understand the main regularities in the genetic control of antibi(cid:2) otic  synthesis  but  also  obtain  strains  with  a  changed level of their biosynthesis.

The  GntR  family  is  one  of  the  largest  among  the identified transcriptional regulators in actinomycetes. The lndYR gene, which encodes a GntR(cid:2)like regulator of  the  YtrA  subfamily,  was  cloned  from  the  chromo(cid:2) some  of  S.  globisporus  1912—a  landomycin  E  pro(cid:2) ducer.  The  directed  inactivation  of  this  gene  sup(cid:2) pressed  the  landomycine  E  sporulation  and  the  pro(cid:2) duction of S. globisporus. As in vivo and in vitro study results have shown, LndYR represses the gene which encodes  the  ABC  transporter  system  (lndW(cid:2)lndW2). The  overexpression  of  lndYR  in  the  S.  ghanaensis ATCC14672 and S. sioyaensis NRRL(cid:2)B55408 strains substantially affected secondary metabolism and mor(cid:2) phological characteristics in bacteria [6]. The  pleiotropic  regulatory  wblAgh  gene,  which encodes a homologue of the WhiB family, was cloned from the genome of S. ghanaensis (a moenomycin pro(cid:2) ducer). The directed inactivation of this gene blocked the sporulation and increased the synthesis of antibi(cid:2) otics,  whereas  its  overexpression  halved  the  produc(cid:2) tion of moenomycins (by 50%) [7].

An  analysis  of  the  sequenced  genomes  of  actino(cid:2) mycetes has shown a great number of homologues of the lndYR and wblAgh genes. It is obvious that protein products of the indicated genes play an important role in  secondary  metabolism  in  bacteria.  However,  the role  of  these  regulators  in  the  genetic  control  of anthracycline  antibiotics  has  not  been  established  so far. The aim of this work was to study the impact of the heterologous expression of the lndYR of S. globisporus 1912 and wblAgh of S. ghanaensis genes on the synthesis of  nogalamycin  in  S.  nogalater,  aranciamycin  in S. echinatus, and doxorubicin in S. peucetius. Bacterial  strains  and  culturing  conditions.  In  our work,  we  used  strains  of  wild(cid:2)type  S.  nogalater  Lv65 (nogalamycin  producer),  S.  echinatus  DSM40730 Fig. 1. Structural formulas of nogalamycin (a), aranciamycin (b), and doxorubicin (c).

(aranciamycin producer), and S. peucetius subsp. cae(cid:2) sius  ATCC27952  (doxorubicin  producer),  as  well  as strains of Escherichia coli: DH5α (F–ϕ80d Δ(lacZ)M15 recA1 endA1gyrA96thi1deoR (lacZYA(cid:2)argF) U169), and ET12567 (dam– 13:: Tn9(Cmr) dcm– 6 hsdM), which had  the  conjugative  pUB307  plasmid  (similar  to  the RK2 plasmid). All the plasmids used in the work had the apramycin resistance gene (Apmr). The strains of Streptomyces, as well as those of E. coli and Sarcina lutea,  are  preserved  in  the  Culture  Collection  of Microorganisms  (producers  of  antibiotics  at  the Franko National University, Lviv). The actinomycetic cultures and the E. coli, S. lutea, and B. subtilis strains were grown at 28 and 37°C, respectively. To produce anthracyclines  by  the  S.  nogalater  Lv65,  S.  echinatus DSM40730,  and  S.  peucetius  caesius ATCC27952  strains,  a  tittered  cell  suspension  (3.5– 4.4) × 107 was inoculated in 50 mL of the Tryptic Soy Broth  (TSB)  medium  [14]  and  incubated  for  24  h; then,  the  24(cid:2)h  culture  was  inoculated  in  a  basal medium (SG [14]; 4% of the volume of the basal cul(cid:2) ture) and grown for 95 h. E. coli was transformed according to the standard “calcium” method [15], and E. coli–S. nogalater con(cid:2) jugation was performed as described earlier in [16].

Determination of the resistibility of strains against antibiotics. The spectrum of antibiotic resistance was determined by the method of diffusion into agar, using disks  with  antibiotics.  The  disks  were  placed  on  the upper layer of 0.7–% MC and BC agar with spores of cultures. The diameters of the growth suppression areas with the antibiotics which diffused from the disks were measured on the third and sixth days of incubation. Determination  of  the  antibiotic  activity  in  the S. nogalater  Lv65,  S.  echinatus  DSM40730,  and S. peucetius  subsp.  caesius  ATCC27952  strains.  An express analysis of the listed strains for antibiotic activ(cid:2) ity was performed using the productivity index defini(cid:2) tion [13]. Actinomycetic strains were grown in an SG medium, and antibiotics were extracted from the cul(cid:2) ture liquid chloroform (1 : 1). The extracts were dried at 37°C, and the dry residue was dissolved in methanol and placed on dishes with 0.7% agar, which contained Sarchina lutea cells (109). The dishes were incubated at 28°C during 12 and 72 h.

Thin(cid:2)layer chromatography (TLC) of nogalamycin, araciamycin,  and  doxorubicin.  Nogalamycin  was extracted from the culture liquid with an equal volume of chloroform, evaporated to dryness in a vacuum, and dissolved in methanol. TLC for nogalamycin was per(cid:2) formed in the chloroform : methanol : ethanol : dis(cid:2) tilled water solvent system (120 : 25 : 6 : 4.5); for aran(cid:2) ciamycin, in the chloroform : methanol system (9 : 1); for  doxorubicin,  similarly  to  [17]  (the  length  of  the front  of  the  chromatographic  plates  was  15  cm). Under  controlled  conditions,  Rf  of  particular  com(cid:2) pounds was defined. Antibiotics were revealed visually and by exposing the chromatographic plates to ultravi(cid:2) olet rays. Summary  and  plasmid  DNA  from  actinomycetic cells was isolated, using the method described in [15]. Preparatory  isolation  of  plasmid  DNA  from  actino(cid:2) mycetes  was  performed  by  the  alkaline  lysis  method [14], as well as by the modified phenol(cid:2)free method, when DNA was purified by salting out proteins with sodium acetate [14]. Plasmid DNA was isolated from E. coli according to [14]. Enzymatic treatment of DNA. A restrictive analysis of total and plasmid DNA was performed, as recom(cid:2) mended  by  the  producer,  under  the  conditions  of DNA  ligation  with  T4  DNA(cid:2)ligase  in  a  standard buffer, according to the described method in [15]. Computer  analysis  of  DNA  sequences.  A  primary analysis of nucleotide sequences and determination of identification sites for restriction endonucleases were performed  using  the  DNASTAR  and  VECTORNTI programs.

For expressing the lndYR and wblAgh genes in cells of  the antibiotic  pKC1218ElndYR(cid:2)2  [6]  and  pKCwblAgh  plasmids were transferred into cells of the S. nogalater Lv65, S. echinatus  DSM40730  and  S.  peucetius  subsp.  caesius ATCC27952  strains  by  the  method  of  intergeneric conjugation  with  E.  coli.  The  donor  was  the  E.  coli ET12567 (pUB307) strain, carrying the pUB307 plas(cid:2) mid that contains the tra genes of the RK2 plasmid. The  expression  of  the  lndYR  gene  cloned  in  the pKC1218ElndYR(cid:2)2 composition comes from the con(cid:2) stitutive promoter (ermEp) of the erythromycin resis(cid:2) tance gene of Saccharopolyspora erythraea [14]. As  a  result  of  this  conjugative  transfer,  we  have obtained  apramycin(cid:2)resistant  transconjugants  of S. nogalater  at  a  frequency  of  (3.0  ±  0.3)  ×  10–6;  of HETEROLOGOUS  EXPRESSION  OF  THE  lndYR  AND  wblAgh  GENES S. echinatus, at a frequency of (2.4 ± 0.2) × 10–3; and of S. peucetius, at a frequency of (5.2 ± 0.3) × 10–4. The presence  of  plasmids  in  the  obtained  recombinant strains was confirmed by transforming E. coli DH5α cells  with  total  DNA  isolated  from  cells  of  the obtained  transconjugates  and  the  subsequent  restric(cid:2) tion mapping of plasmid DNA.

A study of the stability in inheriting the plasmids by transconjugates  has  shown  that  the  Apmr  phenotype, which is supported by the plasmid, is fully lost by the recombinant  strains  after  five  sowings  due  to  the absence of selective pressure (without adding apramy(cid:2) cin to the medium). On the contrary, the plasmids are stably  inherited  under  the  conditions  of  growing transconjugate strains in the presence of antibiotics at a final concentration of 50 μg/mL. For further work, we  chose  three  independent  transconjugates  of  the strains S. nogalater Lv65, S. echinatus DSM40730, and S. peucetius subsp. caesius ATCC27952, for which the presence of the corresponding plasmids has been con(cid:2) firmed.  The  strains  containing  pKC1218lndY2  were designated as S. nogalater YR1, S. echinatus YR2, and S. peucetius YR3, while the strains containing pKCw(cid:2) blAgh were designated as S. nogalater GH1, S. echina(cid:2) tus GH2, and S. peucetius GH3, respectively. To study the impact of pleiotropic regulators on the synthesis  of  nogalamycin,  doxorubicin,  and  arancia(cid:2) mycin,  we  determined  the  antibiotic  activity  of  the corresponding  strains,  using  anthracycline(cid:2)sensitive test cultures. The average values of productivity indi(cid:2) ces for the antibiotic extracts obtained from the stud(cid:2) ied S. nogalater strains varied (Fig. 2a). For example, these indicators were 2.2 ± 0.1 for the extracts of the metabolites obtained from the S. nogalater Lv65 strain,

Areas  of  test(cid:2)culture  growth  suppression  with extracts  of  the  antibiotics  derived  from  the  following strains  (a):  (1)  S.  nogalater  Lv65,  (2)  S.  nogalater  YR1, (3) S. nogalater GH1, and (4) negative control (methanol, used  as  a  solvent  for  nogalamycin);  the  test  culture  is Sarcina lutea; (b) TLC results for extracts of the antibiotics derived from the strains: (1) S. nogalater YR1 and Lv65; the arrow designates a new compound detected by TLC. 5 6 v L r e t a l a g o n . 1.8 ± 0.1 from the S. nogalater YR strain, and 1.6 ± 0.2 from the S. nogalater GH1strain. Thus, the introduc(cid:2) tion of the lndYR gene under the control of the consti(cid:2) tutive ermEp promoter and the wblAgh gene under the control  of  its  own  promoter  into  the  composition  of replicative  and  conjugative  plasmids  suppresses  the processes of antibiotic production in S. nogalater cells and may evidence the presence of homologues of these genes in the nogalamycin producer’s genome.

The  fine(cid:2)layer  chromatographic  results  of  the extracts of the antibiotics isolated from the S. nogalater Lv65 and S. nogalater YR1 strains (Fig. 2b) point to the suppression of the synthesis of not only nogalamycin but  also  that  of  its  precursors.  The  expression  of  the lndYR gene leads to the emergence of a new compound detected  by  fine(cid:2)layer  chromatography.  It  is  obvious that LndYR activates the transcription of mute genes of secondary metabolism in the S. nogalater chromosome. A similar effect was observed for the expression of par(cid:2) ticular  pleiotropic  regulators  in  actinomycetic  cells [5], whereas the use of heterologous expression of reg(cid:2) ulatory  genes  is  an  effective  approach  for  obtaining new antibiotic producers. At the same time, we did not observe the emergence of new metabolites in the GH1 extracts. For the effect of regulators on the level of biosyn(cid:2) thesis of other anthracycline antibiotics, we tested the antibiotic activity of extracts of metabolites from the S. peucetius YR3 and GH3 strains, as well as the S. ech(cid:2) inatus YR2 and GH2 strains. As test cultures, we used Sarcina lutea for the S. echinatus strains and Bacillus cereus for the S. peucetius strains. The average produc(cid:2) tivity  indices  for  the  extracts  of  the  antibiotics obtained from S. peucetius subsp. caesius ATCC27952 were 1.4 ± 0.1; from S. peucetius YR3, 1.2 ± 0.1; and from  S.  peucetius  GH3,  1.0  ±  0.1.  This  indicates  a

Fig.  3.  Areas  of  test(cid:2)culture  growth  suppression  with extracts  of  the  antibiotics  derived  from  the  following strains  (a):  (1)  S.  echinatus  DSM40730,  (2)  S.  echinatus YR2,  (3)  S.  echinatus  GH2,  and  (4)  negative  control (methanol, used as a solvent for aranciamycin); (b) areas of test(cid:2)culture growth suppression with extracts of the antibi(cid:2) otics  derived  from  the  following  strains:  (1)  S.  peucetius subsp. caetius, (2) S. peucetius YR3, (3) S. peucetius GH3, and (4) negative control (methanol, used a solvent for dox(cid:2) orubicin). decrease in the level of antibiotic synthesis as a result of the expression of the genes in question in the doxo(cid:2) rubicin producer’s cells. We obtained a similar result when studying the antibiotic activity of the S. echina(cid:2) tus DSM40730 and S. echinatus YR2 and GH2 strains (Fig. 3). The average values of the productivity indices were 2.0 ± 0.1 for the extracts of the antibiotics from S. echinatus DSM40730 and 1.7 ± 0.1 and 1.5 ± 0.1 for the S. echinatus YR2 and GH2 strains, respectively. A comparison of the average values of productivity indices  for  extracts  of  antibiotics  from  the  obtained strains has confirmed that the presence of native vec(cid:2) tors  pKC1218E  and  pKC1139  in  Streptomyces  cells does  not  affect  the  level  of  synthesis  of  the  studied antibiotics.

The expression of the pKC12183ElndY2(cid:2)2 plasmid in the S. peucetius YR3 strain determines the change in its  morphology.  For  example,  when  S.  peucetius  was grown on complete culture media (oatmeal and Ben(cid:2) nett’s), a decrease was observed in the capacity of the bacteria to form an aerial mycelium and spores which may point to the pleiotropic character of the studied gene’s  expression.  At  the  same  time,  we  did  not detected any effect of the lndYR gene’s expression on the  morphological  characteristics  of  the  S.  nogalater and  S.  echinatus  strains.  According  to  the  previous studies, the regulatory lndYR gene participates in the synthesis of antibiotics and morphogenesis in actino(cid:2) mycetes [6]. This regulator was successfully expressed in  other  Streptomyces  strains.  In  particular,  the expression  of  the  lndYR  gene  in  cells  of  S.  coelicolor M145 (producer of actinorhodin and undecylprodigi(cid:2) osin) allowed researchers to observe its effect on both the synthesis of the corresponding antibiotics and the morphological characteristics of the bacteria [18].

The participation of representatives from the WhiB and GntR families of protein regulators in the genetic control of secondary metabolism was studied in model actynomycetic  strains  [5,  18].  A  comparison  of  the amino  acid  sequences  of  these  proteins  that  were cloned from the genomes of a broad range of actino(cid:2) mycetes confirmed their high conservation [5, 6, 18]. These  regulators  are  also  widespread  among  actino(cid:2) mycetes [5]. The suppression of antibiotic production processes by products of the lndYR and wblAgh genes in S.  nogalater  Lv65,  S.  echinatus  DSM40730,  and S. peucetius  subsp.  caetius  ATCC27952  indicates  the presence of their homologues in the genomes, which fulfill such functions, as well as it discloses the possi(cid:2) bility for studying new links for the regulation of sec(cid:2) ondary metabolism in these bacteria. The identifica(cid:2) tion of the indicated genes for the purpose of their sub(cid:2) sequent directed inactivation can be a successful tool for obtaining strains with an increased level of synthe(cid:2) sis of clinically important compounds, as well as this can allow us to establish some stages in the regulation of secondary metabolism in anthracycline antibiotics. It is evident that to fully understand the genetic regu(cid:2) lation processes in the synthesis of anthracycline anti(cid:2) biotics, it is necessary to perform a simultaneous coex(cid:2) pression  of  different  regulatory  elements.  Genetic manipulations with regulatory genes, together with the optimization  of  the  culturing  conditions,  are  an important  mechanism  for  designing  antibiotic  over(cid:2) producers  and  the  basis  for  the  development  of  bio(cid:2) technological production of anthracyclines.
